<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-713-783  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 713 783.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>LAN Times  Dec 10 1990 v7 n15 p44(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Comparing host- and board-based communications.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>McIntosh, Chris.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The client-server architecture provides fast response times andhigh performance to relatively inexpensive machines throughinteraction with a database server.andP;  Communications betweenclients and server are either controlled by the host CPU using adatalink network adapter card and protocol software or by anetwork processor card that combines physical Ethernet access andTCP/IP protocol processing.andP;  Host-based communications generallycost less than board-based communications because there is lesshardware on an adapter card than on an intelligent networkprocessor; this cost advantageis somewhat mitigated by the cost ofusing host CPU capacity for packet processing rather thanoffloading to a dedicated processor.andP;  Other considerations includethe number of network connections involved and overall systemperformance.andP;  Host-based communications are best suited to networkclients with relatively fewer users and simultaneous connections,and in instances where economy, rather that performance, is thecritical issue.andP;  Board-based communications offer quicker responsetime, consistently outperform host-based communications except interms of raw throughput, and are well-suited to high-performanceservers.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Client/Server ArchitectureCommunications ModesComparisonCommunications Boards/Cards.andO;Feature:   illustrationcharttablegraph.andO;Caption:   Board based vs. host based architecture. (chart)Network processing test. (table)Response times using 25MHz/386 servers with 19 clients. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>